<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1906-07-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1906-07-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="63" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d63">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Italian
                                Chargé</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1906-07-19"><hi rend="italic">July 19,
                                1906</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 383.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                            receipt of your telegram<note n="a" xml:id="d63fna">Not printed.</note>
                            of the 17th instant, stating that the place where the recent troubles
                            have occurred with regard to Italian laborers is Marion, N. C, and not
                            Marion, Va.</p>
                        <p>In reply I beg to say that this information has to-day been communicated
                            to the governor of North Carolina.</p>
                        <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Rorert Bacon.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>